n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_Jasmine"}
{"title_page": "Idiacanthus atlanticus", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name=''Idiacanthus atlanticus''\n| image=Idiacanthus atlanticus.jpg\n| image_caption=\n\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|author=Harold, A..|author2=Strongin, K.|author3=Polidoro, B|author4=Carpenter, buttface K.E..|year=2015|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/21133032/0|title=Idiacanthus atlanticus|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n| regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n| phylum=[[Chordate|Chordata]]\n| classis=[[Actinopterygii]]\n| ordo=[[Stomiiformes]]\n| familia=[[Stomiidae]]\n| genus=''[[Idiacanthus]]''\n| species='''''I. atlanticus'''''\n| binomial=''Idiacanthus atlanticus''\n| binomial_authority=[[August Bernhard Brauer|A. B. Brauer]], 1906\n}}\n\n'''''Idiacanthus atlanticus''''' (commonly known as the '''black dragonfish''') is a [[barbeled dragonfish]] of the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Stomiidae]], found circumglobally in southern subtropical and temperate oceans between latitudes 25\u00b0S and 60\u00b0E, at depths down to {{convert|2,000|m}}. The species is [[sexually dimorphic]]: females are black with six stripes; male are brown, and lack the females' canine teeth, pelvic fins and barbel. Females are believed to make a [[diel vertical migration]] from deeper than {{convert|500|m}} by day to surface waters at night, whereas males do not migrate, remaining below {{convert|1,000|m}} at all times.<ref>{{cite book | first1=Tony | last1=Ayling | first2=Geoffrey J. | last2=Cox | title=Collins Guide to the Sea Fishes of New Zealand | publisher=William Collins | location=Auckland, New Zealand | date=1982 | isbn=978-0-00216-987-5}}</ref><ref>{{FishBase | genus=Idiacanthus | species=atlanticus | month=May | year=2006}}</ref>\n\nLength is up to {{convert|40|cm}} for the female, but only {{convert|5|cm}} for the male. Black dragonfish are [[bioluminescent]], but unlike most such predators, which use their light primarily to attract prey, they can see their own light. As a result, the fish can use their light to hunt. The light is nearly in the [[infrared]] and barely visible to the human eye.<ref name=Creighton>{{cite web |last1=Creighton |first1=Jolene |title=Aliens of the Deep: The Black Dragonfish |url=http://www.fromquarkstoquasars.com/aliens-of-the-deep-the-black-dragonfish/ |publisher=From Quarks to Quasars |accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the larval stage, the eyes of the larvae appear as long stalks that dangle out of the body. Eventually, they retreat as the fish ages and reaches maturity.<ref name=Creighton/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q518838}}\n\n[[Category:Stomiidae]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by August Brauer]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1906]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name=''Idiacanthus atlanticus''\n| image=Idiacanthus atlanticus.jpg\n| image_caption=\n\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|author=Harold, A..|author2=Strongin, K.|author3=Polidoro, B|author4=Carpenter, K.E..|year=2015|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/21133032/0|title=Idiacanthus atlanticus|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n| regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n| phylum=[[Chordate|Chordata]]\n| classis=[[Actinopterygii]]\n| ordo=[[Stomiiformes]]\n| familia=[[Stomiidae]]\n| genus=''[[Idiacanthus]]''\n| species='''''I. atlanticus'''''\n| binomial=''Idiacanthus atlanticus''\n| binomial_authority=[[August Bernhard Brauer|A. B. Brauer]], 1906\n}}\n\n'''''Idiacanthus atlanticus''''' (commonly known as the '''black dragonfish''') is a [[barbeled dragonfish]] of the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Stomiidae]], found circumglobally in southern subtropical and temperate oceans between latitudes 25\u00b0S and 60\u00b0E, at depths down to {{convert|2,000|m}}. The species is [[sexually dimorphic]]: females are black with six stripes; male are brown, and lack the females' canine teeth, pelvic fins and barbel. Females are believed to make a [[diel vertical migration]] from deeper than {{convert|500|m}} by day to surface waters at night, whereas males do not migrate, remaining below {{convert|1,000|m}} at all times.<ref>{{cite book | first1=Tony | last1=Ayling | first2=Geoffrey J. | last2=Cox | title=Collins Guide to the Sea Fishes of New Zealand | publisher=William Collins | location=Auckland, New Zealand | date=1982 | isbn=978-0-00216-987-5}}</ref><ref>{{FishBase | genus=Idiacanthus | species=atlanticus | month=May | year=2006}}</ref>\n\nLength is up to {{convert|40|cm}} for the female, but only {{convert|5|cm}} for the male. Black dragonfish are [[bioluminescent]], but unlike most such predators, which use their light primarily to attract prey, they can see their own light. As a result, the fish can use their light to hunt. The light is nearly in the [[infrared]] and barely visible to the human eye.<ref name=Creighton>{{cite web |last1=Creighton |first1=Jolene |title=Aliens of the Deep: The Black Dragonfish |url=http://www.fromquarkstoquasars.com/aliens-of-the-deep-the-black-dragonfish/ |publisher=From Quarks to Quasars |accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the larval stage, the eyes of the larvae appear as long stalks that dangle out of the body. Eventually, they retreat as the fish ages and reaches maturity.<ref name=Creighton/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q518838}}\n\n[[Category:Stomiidae]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by August Brauer]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1906]]\n", "name_user": "24.117.47.159", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idiacanthus_atlanticus"}
{"title_page": "Horsehead Nebula", "text_new": "{{short description|Dark nebula in the constellation Orion. Probably Not}}\n{{Infobox nebula\n| image = [[File:Barnard 33.jpg|250px]]\n| caption = The Horsehead Nebula. The reflection nebula [[NGC 2023]] is in the bottom left corner and the nebula itself near the center, in the shape of the head of a horse.\n| name = Horsehead Nebula\n| type = dark\n| type2 = diffuse/yerr\n| epoch = J2000.0\n| ra = 05<sup>h</sup> 40<sup>m</sup> 59.0<sup>s</sup>\n| dec = \u221202\u00b0 27\u2032 30.0\"\n| dist_pc = {{val|422|17}}<ref name=\"Gaia DR2\">{{Cite DR2}}</ref>\n| dist_ly = {{val|1375|54}}<ref name=\"Gaia DR2\"/><ref group=\"note\">Based on the parallax of 2MASS J05405172-0226489, a [[young stellar object]] embedded in the 'head' of the nebula.</ref>\n| appmag_v =\n| size_v = 8 \u00d7 6 [[Minute of arc|arcmins]]\n| constellation = [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]\n| radius_ly = 3.5\n| names = Barnard 33, LDN 1630}}\n\nThe '''Horsehead Nebula''' (also known as '''Barnard 33''') is a small [[dark nebula]] in the constellation [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Arnett |first=Bill |title=Horsehead Nebula |url=http://astro.nineplanets.org/twn/b33x.html |date=2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref> The nebula is located just to the south of [[Zeta Orionis|Alnitak]], the easternmost star of [[Orion's Belt]], and is part of the much larger [[Orion Molecular Cloud Complex]].  It appears within the southern region of the dense dust cloud known as Lynds 1630, along the edge of the much larger, active star-forming [[H II region]] called [[IC 434]].<ref name=\"ESO2002\">{{cite web\n|title=VLT Images the Horsehead Nebula\n|website=European Southern Observatory \n|url= https://www.eso.org/public/australia/news/eso0202/\n|publisher=European Southern Observatory \n|date=25 January 2002\n|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Horsehead Nebula is approximately 422 parsecs or 1375 [[light year]]s from Earth.<ref name=\"ESO2002\"/><ref name=\"Gaia DR2\"/> It is one of the most identifiable nebulae because of its resemblance to a horse's head.<ref name=\"noao.edu\">{{cite web |last=Sharp |first=Nigel |title=The Horsehead Nebula |website=National Optical Astronomy Observatory |url= http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im0057.html |publisher=Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy |date=2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe nebula was first recorded in 1888 by [[Scotland|Scottish]] astronomer [[Williamina Fleming]] on a photographic plate taken at the [[Harvard College]] Observatory.<ref name=\"Cannon\">{{cite journal|last=Cannon|first=Annie J.|date=June 1911|title=Williamina Paton Fleming |journal=Science|publication-date=June 30, 1911|volume=33|issue=861|pages=987\u2013988|bibcode=1911Sci....33..987C|doi=10.1126/science.33.861.987|pmid=17799863|authorlink=Annie Jump Cannon|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1448062}}</ref> One of the first description was made by [[E.E. Barnard]], describing it as: \"Dark mass, diam. 4\u2032, on nebulous strip extending\nsouth from [[Alnitak|\u03b6 Orionis.]]\", cataloguing the dark nebula as Barnard 33.<ref name=\"Barnard1919\">{{cite journal\n|last=Barnard| first=E. E.\n|date=1919\n|title=On the dark markings of the sky, with a catalogue of 182 such objects.\n|journal=Astrophysical Journal\n|volume=49\n|pages=1\u201324\n|bibcode=1919ApJ....49....1B\n|doi=10.1086/142439}}</ref> \n\n==Structure==\n[[Image:Orion Belt.jpg|thumb|[[Orion's Belt]] with [[Alnitak]] on the left-hand side and the Horsehead Nebula directly below it.]]\n\nThe dark cloud of dust and gas is a region in the Orion Molecular Cloud Complex where star formation is taking place. It is located in the constellation of [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]], which is prominent in the winter evening sky in the Northern Hemisphere and the summer evening sky in the Southern Hemisphere. \n\nColour images reveal a deep-red colour that originates from ionised [[hydrogen]] gas ([[H-alpha|H\u03b1]]) predominantly behind the nebula, and caused by the nearby bright star [[Sigma Orionis]]. [[Magnetic field]]s channel the gases, leaving the nebula into streams, shown as foreground streaks against the background glow.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im0661.html|title = The Horsehead Nebula/IC434|accessdate = 12 May 2014|website = National Optical Astronomy Observatory|publisher = NOAO|last = |first = }}</ref> A glowing strip of hydrogen gas marks the edge of the massive cloud, and the densities of nearby stars are noticeably different on either side. \n\nHeavy concentrations of [[interstellar dust|dust]] in the Horsehead Nebula region and neighbouring Orion Nebula are localized into [[interstellar cloud]]s, resulting in alternating sections of nearly complete opacity and transparency.<ref name=\"MorganLod\u00e9n1966\">{{cite journal|last1=Morgan|first1=W.W.|last2=Lod\u00e9n|first2=Kerstin|title=Some Characteristics of the Orion Association|journal=Vistas in Astronomy|volume=8|issue=1|date=1966|pages=83\u201388|issn=0083-6656|doi=10.1016/0083-6656(66)90023-7|bibcode = 1966VA......8...83M }}</ref> The darkness of the Horsehead is caused mostly by thick dust blocking the light of stars behind it.<ref name=\"Mayo Greenberg2002\">{{cite journal|last1=Mayo Greenberg|first1=J|title=Cosmic dust and our origins|journal=Surface Science|volume=500|issue=1\u20133|date=2002|pages=793\u2013822|issn=0039-6028|doi=10.1016/S0039-6028(01)01555-2|bibcode = 2002SurSc.500..793M }}</ref> The lower part of the Horsehead's neck casts a shadow to the left.<ref>{{Cite APOD|title = The Horsehead Nebula|date = 21 July 2009|access-date = 12 May 2014}}</ref> The visible dark nebula emerging from the gaseous complex is an active site of the formation of \"low-mass\" stars. Bright spots in the Horsehead Nebula's base are young stars just in the process of forming.\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Horse Head and Flame Nebula Hydrogen alpha 384mm scope stephan hamel wiki.jpg|Horse Head Nebula and Flame Nebula showing their surrounding nebulosity in Hydrogen alpha as seen in amateur telescopes.\nImage:Horsehead and flame Nebulea 384mm scope Ha-RGB.jpg|Horsehead and flame Nebulae 384mm scope Ha-RGB imaged with amateur equipment.\nFile:Horsehead-Hubble.jpg|Interstellar dust of the Horsehead Nebula as revealed by the [[Hubble Space Telescope]].\nFile:Nebulosa testa di cavallo con SPECULOOS.jpg|The Horsehead Nebula seen by [[SPECULOOS]]'s Callisto telescope\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nebulae in fiction#Horsehead Nebula|Horsehead Nebula in fiction]]\n*[[List of Hubble anniversary images]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.sofia.usra.edu/science/proposing-and-observing/proposal-calls/sofia-directors-discretionary-time/horsehead-nebula SOFIA/upGREAT &#91;C II&#93; Velocity Resolved Map of the Horsehead Nebula]\n* [http://www.glyphweb.com/esky/nebulae/ic434.html The Horsehead Nebula @ The Electronic Sky]\n* [http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/newsdesk/archive/releases/2001/12/image/a Hubble Observes the Horsehead Nebula]\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?1990PASP..102.1337W The discovery of early photographs of the Horsehead nebula, by Waldee and Hazen]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150106052626/http://freescruz.com/~4cygni/horsehead/B33-19thC_4.htm The Horsehead Nebula in the 19th Century, by Waldee]\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1890AnHar..18..113P&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=44215828ae04166 Detection of new nebulae by photography, by Pickering]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014743/http://www.spacetelescope.org/bin/images.pl?searchtype=freesearch&string=Horsehead+Nebula Horsehead Nebula at ESA/Hubble]\n* [http://ryutao.main.jp/english/stl_batou_l.html The Horsehead Nebula at the Astro-Photography site of Mr. T. Yoshida.]\n* [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:HorseheadHunterWilson.jpg The Horsehead-Nebula and neighboring structures in a classical view]\n* [http://wikisky.org/?img_source=IMG_all&zoom=8&img_borders=1&ra=5.68&de=-2.5 The Horsehead Nebula on interactive astro-photography survey at Wikisky.org]\n* [http://www.constellation-guide.com/horsehead-nebula-barnard-33/ The Horsehead Nebula at Constellation Guide]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Orion (constellation)]]\n[[Category:Dark nebulae]]\n[[Category:Horsehead Nebula| ]]\n[[Category:Orion Molecular Cloud Complex|Barnard 33]]\n[[Category:Star formation]]\n[[Category:Barnard objects]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dark nebula in the constellation Orion}}\n{{Infobox nebula\n| image = [[File:Barnard 33.jpg|250px]]\n| caption = The Horsehead Nebula. The reflection nebula [[NGC 2023]] is in the bottom left corner and the nebula itself near the center, in the shape of the head of a horse.\n| name = Horsehead Nebula\n| type = dark\n| type2 = diffuse\n| epoch = J2000.0\n| ra = 05<sup>h</sup> 40<sup>m</sup> 59.0<sup>s</sup>\n| dec = \u221202\u00b0 27\u2032 30.0\"\n| dist_pc = {{val|422|17}}<ref name=\"Gaia DR2\">{{Cite DR2}}</ref>\n| dist_ly = {{val|1375|54}}<ref name=\"Gaia DR2\"/><ref group=\"note\">Based on the parallax of 2MASS J05405172-0226489, a [[young stellar object]] embedded in the 'head' of the nebula.</ref>\n| appmag_v =\n| size_v = 8 \u00d7 6 [[Minute of arc|arcmins]]\n| constellation = [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]\n| radius_ly = 3.5\n| names = Barnard 33, LDN 1630}}\n\nThe '''Horsehead Nebula''' (also known as '''Barnard 33''') is a small [[dark nebula]] in the constellation [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Arnett |first=Bill |title=Horsehead Nebula |url=http://astro.nineplanets.org/twn/b33x.html |date=2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref> The nebula is located just to the south of [[Zeta Orionis|Alnitak]], the easternmost star of [[Orion's Belt]], and is part of the much larger [[Orion Molecular Cloud Complex]].  It appears within the southern region of the dense dust cloud known as Lynds 1630, along the edge of the much larger, active star-forming [[H II region]] called [[IC 434]].<ref name=\"ESO2002\">{{cite web\n|title=VLT Images the Horsehead Nebula\n|website=European Southern Observatory \n|url= https://www.eso.org/public/australia/news/eso0202/\n|publisher=European Southern Observatory \n|date=25 January 2002\n|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Horsehead Nebula is approximately 422 parsecs or 1375 [[light year]]s from Earth.<ref name=\"ESO2002\"/><ref name=\"Gaia DR2\"/> It is one of the most identifiable nebulae because of its resemblance to a horse's head.<ref name=\"noao.edu\">{{cite web |last=Sharp |first=Nigel |title=The Horsehead Nebula |website=National Optical Astronomy Observatory |url= http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im0057.html |publisher=Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy |date=2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe nebula was first recorded in 1888 by [[Scotland|Scottish]] astronomer [[Williamina Fleming]] on a photographic plate taken at the [[Harvard College]] Observatory.<ref name=\"Cannon\">{{cite journal|last=Cannon|first=Annie J.|date=June 1911|title=Williamina Paton Fleming |journal=Science|publication-date=June 30, 1911|volume=33|issue=861|pages=987\u2013988|bibcode=1911Sci....33..987C|doi=10.1126/science.33.861.987|pmid=17799863|authorlink=Annie Jump Cannon|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1448062}}</ref> One of the first description was made by [[E.E. Barnard]], describing it as: \"Dark mass, diam. 4\u2032, on nebulous strip extending\nsouth from [[Alnitak|\u03b6 Orionis.]]\", cataloguing the dark nebula as Barnard 33.<ref name=\"Barnard1919\">{{cite journal\n|last=Barnard| first=E. E.\n|date=1919\n|title=On the dark markings of the sky, with a catalogue of 182 such objects.\n|journal=Astrophysical Journal\n|volume=49\n|pages=1\u201324\n|bibcode=1919ApJ....49....1B\n|doi=10.1086/142439}}</ref> \n\n==Structure==\n[[Image:Orion Belt.jpg|thumb|[[Orion's Belt]] with [[Alnitak]] on the left-hand side and the Horsehead Nebula directly below it.]]\n\nThe dark cloud of dust and gas is a region in the Orion Molecular Cloud Complex where star formation is taking place. It is located in the constellation of [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]], which is prominent in the winter evening sky in the Northern Hemisphere and the summer evening sky in the Southern Hemisphere. \n\nColour images reveal a deep-red colour that originates from ionised [[hydrogen]] gas ([[H-alpha|H\u03b1]]) predominantly behind the nebula, and caused by the nearby bright star [[Sigma Orionis]]. [[Magnetic field]]s channel the gases, leaving the nebula into streams, shown as foreground streaks against the background glow.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im0661.html|title = The Horsehead Nebula/IC434|accessdate = 12 May 2014|website = National Optical Astronomy Observatory|publisher = NOAO|last = |first = }}</ref> A glowing strip of hydrogen gas marks the edge of the massive cloud, and the densities of nearby stars are noticeably different on either side. \n\nHeavy concentrations of [[interstellar dust|dust]] in the Horsehead Nebula region and neighbouring Orion Nebula are localized into [[interstellar cloud]]s, resulting in alternating sections of nearly complete opacity and transparency.<ref name=\"MorganLod\u00e9n1966\">{{cite journal|last1=Morgan|first1=W.W.|last2=Lod\u00e9n|first2=Kerstin|title=Some Characteristics of the Orion Association|journal=Vistas in Astronomy|volume=8|issue=1|date=1966|pages=83\u201388|issn=0083-6656|doi=10.1016/0083-6656(66)90023-7|bibcode = 1966VA......8...83M }}</ref> The darkness of the Horsehead is caused mostly by thick dust blocking the light of stars behind it.<ref name=\"Mayo Greenberg2002\">{{cite journal|last1=Mayo Greenberg|first1=J|title=Cosmic dust and our origins|journal=Surface Science|volume=500|issue=1\u20133|date=2002|pages=793\u2013822|issn=0039-6028|doi=10.1016/S0039-6028(01)01555-2|bibcode = 2002SurSc.500..793M }}</ref> The lower part of the Horsehead's neck casts a shadow to the left.<ref>{{Cite APOD|title = The Horsehead Nebula|date = 21 July 2009|access-date = 12 May 2014}}</ref> The visible dark nebula emerging from the gaseous complex is an active site of the formation of \"low-mass\" stars. Bright spots in the Horsehead Nebula's base are young stars just in the process of forming.\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Horse Head and Flame Nebula Hydrogen alpha 384mm scope stephan hamel wiki.jpg|Horse Head Nebula and Flame Nebula showing their surrounding nebulosity in Hydrogen alpha as seen in amateur telescopes.\nImage:Horsehead and flame Nebulea 384mm scope Ha-RGB.jpg|Horsehead and flame Nebulae 384mm scope Ha-RGB imaged with amateur equipment.\nFile:Horsehead-Hubble.jpg|Interstellar dust of the Horsehead Nebula as revealed by the [[Hubble Space Telescope]].\nFile:Nebulosa testa di cavallo con SPECULOOS.jpg|The Horsehead Nebula seen by [[SPECULOOS]]'s Callisto telescope\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nebulae in fiction#Horsehead Nebula|Horsehead Nebula in fiction]]\n*[[List of Hubble anniversary images]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.sofia.usra.edu/science/proposing-and-observing/proposal-calls/sofia-directors-discretionary-time/horsehead-nebula SOFIA/upGREAT &#91;C II&#93; Velocity Resolved Map of the Horsehead Nebula]\n* [http://www.glyphweb.com/esky/nebulae/ic434.html The Horsehead Nebula @ The Electronic Sky]\n* [http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/newsdesk/archive/releases/2001/12/image/a Hubble Observes the Horsehead Nebula]\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?1990PASP..102.1337W The discovery of early photographs of the Horsehead nebula, by Waldee and Hazen]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/2015010605262